Understanding the Linux Prompt: [root@localhost 
When you open a terminal in RedHat (RHEL), you see a prompt like:
[root@localhost ~]#
Here is the full breakdown with deeper technical meaning.________________________________________
ğŸ”¹ 1) root â†’ Superuser Account (UID = 0)
â€¢	root is the administrator of the entire Linux system.
â€¢	It has unrestricted access to all files, processes, services, and settings.
â€¢	In Linux, users are identified by a unique UID (User ID).
âœ” Root always has UID = 0
You can check this by running:
id root 
Output example:
uid=0(root) gid=0(root) groups=0(root)
âœ” What UID 0 means:
â€¢	Full control over system
â€¢	Can install/remove packages
â€¢	Can modify system configuration
â€¢	Can create/delete any file
â€¢	Can start/stop system services
â€¢	No restrictions from file permissions
âœ” Security Note:
Never use root for regular work â€” one wrong command can break the entire system.
ğŸ”¹ 2) @localhost â†’ Hostname of the Machine
â€¢	localhost is the default hostname for a system not yet configured.
â€¢	In real servers, you may see names like:
â€¢	app-server1
â€¢	db-prod
â€¢	mail-node01
Check hostname:
